# Key Terraform Module Composition Patterns

## Flat Module Architecture

The recommended approach keeps module hierarchies flat with a single level of child modules. Rather than modules embedding their own dependencies, they **receive dependencies from the root module**, enabling flexible interconnection.

```hcl
module "network" {
  source = "./modules/aws-network"
  base_cidr_block = "10.0.0.0/8"
}

module "consul_cluster" {
  source = "./modules/aws-consul-cluster"
  vpc_id     = module.network.vpc_id
  subnet_ids = module.network.subnet_ids
}
```

## Dependency Inversion Principle

Rather than having modules create their own dependencies, pass them as input variables. This approach allows future refactoring without changing the module itself:

> "the module doesn't know or care how those identifiers are obtained by the calling module"

For example, network identifiers can come from either newly created resources or existing data sources:

```hcl
# Option 1: Created resources
module "consul_cluster" {
  source = "./modules/aws-consul-cluster"
  vpc_id     = module.network.vpc_id
  subnet_ids = module.network.subnet_ids
}

# Option 2: Data sources (future refactor)
data "aws_vpc" "main" {
  tags = { Environment = "production" }
}

module "consul_cluster" {
  source = "./modules/aws-consul-cluster"
  vpc_id     = data.aws_vpc.main.id
  subnet_ids = data.aws_subnet_ids.main.ids
}
```

## Conditional Object Creation

Instead of embedding complex conditional logic, define input variables accepting partial object schemas. Callers decide whether to create or reference objects:

```hcl
variable "ami" {
  type = object({
    id           = string
    architecture = string
  })
}
```

This enables either resource creation or data source reference without module changes—supporting cost optimization across development and production environments.

